<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870331-0135 </DOCNO><HL> C.O.M.B. Co.'s OptionsBegin Trading on Amex</HL><DD> 03/31/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> CMCO AMGN MINYSTOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR) </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The American Stock Exchange said it began trading put and call options on the stock of C.O.M.B. Co.    The Plymouth, Minn.-based consumer merchandiser will trade under options symbol COQ.    The exchange also said it will begin trading options, pending regulatory approval, on Amgen, a Thousand Oaks, Calif.-based biotechnology concern, and MiniScribe Corp., a Longmont, Colo.-based disk drive maker.    The options are securities that grant the holder the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell 100 shares of a stock by a certain date and at a specified price. Calls are options to buy, and puts are options to sell. </TEXT></DOC>